In this experiment you will be presented with either an image with more squares than circles, or an image with
more circles than squares. You will see them one at a time.
Your task will be to decide whether more squares or more circles were presented by pushing the correct button as quickly
The ""A"" key will be used to identify more circles and the ""L"" key will be used
to identify more squares. Examples of what the images look like are below:
The [A] key will be used to identify pictures with
The [L] key will be used to identify pictures with

4,1,1187.1299999766052,"

Now, let's take a practice run. You will see a fixation cross, '+', on the screen. You should always focus your
attention on the fixation cross as this will help you identify the image as quickly and accurately as possible. The fixation
cross will be followed by an image with more squares or more circles. Remember, if you think there are more circles
press the ""A"" key. If you think there are more squares press the ""L"" key.

If you understand these directions and are ready to proceed to the practice round, please press the spacebar.
